        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Search intent</strong> (also called user intent or query intent) is the underlying goal a person has when typing a query into a search engine. Google classifies intent into four main categories — informational, navigational, commercial investigation, and transactional — and uses these signals to determine which content format and type belongs at the top of the SERP. Matching your content to intent is the primary prerequisite for ranking.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Keyword Research</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Also Called</div>
            <div class="tms-value">User Intent, Query Intent</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Intermediate</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Read Time</div>
            <div class="tms-value">8 min</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">You can have the best-written, most thoroughly researched page on a topic and still fail to rank — if your content type does not match what the searcher was actually looking for. Search intent is why Google shows product pages for "buy running shoes" and blog posts for "how to choose running shoes" for what looks like the same general topic.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is search intent?</h2>
        <p>Search intent is the purpose behind a search query. When someone types a query into Google, they have a goal — and that goal determines what kind of result will satisfy them. Google's core mission is to satisfy that goal as quickly and completely as possible.</p>

        <p>Google's Search Quality Rater Guidelines — the document used to train human quality evaluators — formally categorise user needs. The framework has evolved over the years, but the practical model most SEOs use today breaks intent into four types:</p>

        <ul>
          <li><strong>Informational:</strong> The user wants to learn something</li>
          <li><strong>Navigational:</strong> The user wants to reach a specific website or page</li>
          <li><strong>Commercial investigation:</strong> The user is researching before making a decision</li>
          <li><strong>Transactional:</strong> The user is ready to take an action (buy, sign up, download)</li>
        </ul>

        <p>A fifth informal category — <strong>local intent</strong> — applies when queries carry implicit or explicit geographic signals, such as "coffee shop near me" or "plumber in Chicago".</p>

        <h2 id="four-types">The four types of search intent explained</h2>

        <h3>1. Informational intent</h3>
        <p>The searcher wants to learn. They are in research mode, not buying mode. The SERP typically shows blog posts, how-to guides, Wikipedia pages, and YouTube videos for these queries.</p>

        <p>Examples: "what is email marketing", "how do black holes form", "best way to learn Spanish"</p>

        <p>Content that works: in-depth explanatory articles, tutorials, videos, comparison guides without a sales angle. These pages are poor conversion targets but excellent for building topical authority and capturing top-of-funnel traffic.</p>

        <h3>2. Navigational intent</h3>
        <p>The searcher already knows where they want to go. They are using the search engine as a shortcut to a specific website or page — often because it is faster than typing the full URL.</p>

        <p>Examples: "Instagram login", "Ahrefs pricing page", "theStacc demo"</p>

        <p>Content that works: your brand's homepage, login pages, or the specific page the user expects to find. Competing for navigational queries on your own brand is straightforward. Trying to intercept someone else's navigational query rarely works and can come across as manipulative.</p>

        <h3>3. Commercial investigation intent</h3>
        <p>The searcher is actively comparing options before making a decision. They know a purchase or commitment is coming, but they are not ready yet. They want comparisons, reviews, lists, and expert recommendations.</p>

        <p>Examples: "best project management software", "Shopify vs WooCommerce", "HubSpot reviews", "top email marketing tools for small business"</p>

        <p>Content that works: detailed comparison articles, best-of lists, review posts, and alternative pages. These are high-value keywords for SaaS and e-commerce because the searcher is close to converting — they just need more information to choose.</p>

        <h3>4. Transactional intent</h3>
        <p>The searcher is ready to act. They may already have decided on a product or service and are now looking for the right place to complete the transaction. The SERP often shows shopping results, product pages, and landing pages with CTAs.</p>

        <p>Examples: "buy Nike Air Max 90", "Spotify premium sign up", "download Photoshop trial"</p>

        <p>Content that works: product pages, category pages, landing pages with strong CTAs, and pricing pages. Informational content ranks poorly for these queries because it does not satisfy the immediate action the user wants to take.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Google's perspective</div>
          <p>Google's Search Quality Rater Guidelines introduce the concept of "user need" and describe content rating based on how well it satisfies that need. Pages rated "Fails to Meet" (the lowest rating) often fail because of intent mismatch — not because of writing quality or technical issues.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="how-google-detects">How Google detects and enforces search intent</h2>
        <p>Google does not just read your page's keywords to determine intent — it uses multiple signals to understand what users actually want from a given query.</p>

        <h3>Analysing existing SERP behaviour</h3>
        <p>Google observes how users interact with results over millions of searches. If most users who search for "keyword" click on listicle articles and spend significant time on them (rather than bouncing back), Google learns that listicles satisfy this query. This aggregate behaviour shapes what Google shows for future searches.</p>

        <h3>Pogo-sticking as a penalty signal</h3>
        <p>If a user clicks your result, spends only a few seconds, and returns to the SERP to click another result (pogo-sticking), Google interprets this as your page failing to satisfy the user's need. Systematic pogo-sticking leads to ranking demotions, regardless of other quality signals.</p>

        <h3>Content format recognition</h3>
        <p>Google's systems can identify the content format of a page — article, product listing, video, tool, PDF — and match it against the content format that historically satisfies the query. A transactional query that typically resolves on a product page will struggle to be satisfied by a blog article, even if the article mentions the product.</p>

        <h2 id="how-to-identify">How to identify search intent for any keyword</h2>
        <p>The most reliable method is direct SERP analysis. Follow these steps for any keyword you are targeting:</p>

        <ol>
          <li><strong>Google the keyword in incognito mode</strong> (to avoid personalisation bias) and note the type of pages on page one — product pages, blog posts, category pages, YouTube videos, Wikipedia entries.</li>
          <li><strong>Note the content angle.</strong> Are all the page-one results "how to" guides? "Best X" lists? Reviews? Product comparisons? The angle is as important as the content type.</li>
          <li><strong>Check SERP features.</strong> Shopping ads = transactional. People Also Ask boxes = informational. Local pack = local intent. Featured snippets with definitions = informational.</li>
          <li><strong>Look at the titles of page-one results.</strong> They will signal the format Google rewards — listicles use numbers, guides use "how to", review pages use "X review" or "is X worth it".</li>
          <li><strong>Read the top results.</strong> Note the depth, the CTAs (or lack of them), the structure. This is your content brief for intent alignment.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="mixed-intent">Mixed and blended intent keywords</h2>
        <p>Not every keyword fits neatly into one intent category. Mixed-intent keywords are common — and they require a specific content strategy.</p>

        <p>For example, "best CRM for small business" blends informational and commercial investigation intent. The searcher wants to learn what options exist (informational) and is actively comparing before buying (commercial). Google handles this by typically ranking comparison articles or roundup posts that satisfy both needs at once.</p>

        <p>For mixed-intent keywords, the winning content format is usually a <strong>comprehensive listicle with editorial depth</strong> — more than just a list, with enough context to inform a purchasing decision.</p>

        <h2 id="content-matching">Matching your content to intent</h2>
        <p>Once you have identified the intent behind a keyword, matching your content means getting three things right:</p>

        <ul>
          <li><strong>Content type:</strong> Blog post, product page, category page, landing page, tool, video</li>
          <li><strong>Content format:</strong> How-to guide, step-by-step tutorial, best-of list, comparison table, definition/explainer, review</li>
          <li><strong>Content angle:</strong> The unique hook — freshest, most comprehensive, best for beginners, fastest method, most affordable option</li>
        </ul>

        <p>Matching all three is what makes a page feel immediately relevant when a user lands on it — reducing bounce rate and increasing the engagement signals that feed back into rankings.</p>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common search intent mistakes</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Building a product page for an informational query.</strong> "How to use CRM software" deserves a guide, not a signup page. You will rank poorly and convert even if you somehow rank.</li>
          <li><strong>Building a blog post for a transactional query.</strong> "CRM software free trial" searchers want a trial, not an article about why free trials matter.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring SERP signals and relying on keyword logic.</strong> The word "best" feels commercial, but sometimes Google serves informational content for "best" keywords. Always check the actual SERP.</li>
          <li><strong>Targeting the same keyword with multiple pages of different intent.</strong> If two pages on your site target the same keyword with different content types, they will cannibalise each other's rankings.</li>
          <li><strong>Failing to update content when SERP intent shifts.</strong> Google's interpretation of intent can change over time as user behaviour evolves. A page that used to rank may drop if the SERP intent has shifted and your page no longer matches.</li>
        </ul>

